<Group labelreference="L3" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle1" layout="_pstyle148">Chaotic Processes Cookbook</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle2" layout="_pstyle149">10-2-2012</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">This Maple cookbook contains various routines or 'recipes' for the analysis of non-linear and chaotic dynamical systems. The aim of this document is to provide you with a set of recipes that will enable you to analyze physical systems quickly and effectively.  By no means is this document intended to be a sufficient introduction into Maple, although it should give a reasonable impression of how Maple works and what it can do in this field.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L4" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle4" layout="_pstyle151">General Maple characteristics - introduction</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle5" layout="_pstyle152"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L5" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L293" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle6" layout="_pstyle153">Settings &amp; tips</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> Always use Worksheet mode, never Document mode</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> Tools -&gt; Options -&gt; Interface -&gt; default format for new worksheets: set to Worksheet</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> Tools -&gt; Options -&gt; Display -&gt; Input display: set to &quot;Maple Notation&quot;</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> Tools -&gt; Options -&gt; General -&gt; Auto save: uncheck (i.e. no auto-saving)</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L7" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle6" layout="_pstyle153">Useful keys</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Ctrl-J: insert execution group after cursor</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156">Ctrl-K: insert execution group before cursor</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156">Ctrl-delete: remove line</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156"><Font style="_cstyle3">F3: split </Font>execution <Font style="_cstyle3">group</Font></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156"><Font style="_cstyle3">F4: join </Font>execution <Font style="_cstyle3">group</Font></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156"><Font style="_cstyle3">SHIFT-Enter: new line without execution (for loops)</Font></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle156" layout="_pstyle156">Try them now!</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L297" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L295" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle6" layout="_pstyle153">Help</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Maybe the most important command  is the ? command, which is to get  help about a certain command. </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L296" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">? solve</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L299" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle6" layout="_pstyle153">Comments</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L8" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle157">#</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle157"># the #-sign allows comments</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle157">#</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L9" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle7" layout="_pstyle158">General</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">A session normally starts with a restart command, clearing all data from memory and with including some packages, such as plots for figures and DEtools for differential equations</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L10" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">restart; with(plots): with(LinearAlgebra): with(DEtools):</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">     </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L11" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle27" layout="_pstyle159">Some important details:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">-  All commands need to end with ; or : </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">- : suppresses output from that command.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">- You can put more than one command on an execution line.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L12" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Assigning a value to a variable is done with ':='. A common mistake is to use '=' instead of ':=', but '=' is used for equations, not assignments.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Note the crucial difference below:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L535" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">a = 1/sqrt(2); </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L536" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">a;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L543" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">note: a has not been assigned, i.e. a did not get a value, however</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L13" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">a := 1/sqrt(2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L537" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">a;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L14" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Maple is a mathematical language and will allways try to give an exact answer. So 1/2 and 0.5 are not the same, we will need to specifically ask Maple to convert the result to a float:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L16" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">evalf(a);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L1883" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">Digits:=60;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L1884" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">evalf(Pi);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L17" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle9" layout="_pstyle160">Functions vs expressions</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle9" layout="_pstyle160"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L18" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">A function and an expression, respectively, are defined as</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L19" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">f := x -&gt; x^2;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L20" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">q := x^2;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L21" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Asking for the value of a function is easier (and more elegant) than for an expression </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L22" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">f;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L23" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">f(2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L24" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">subs(x=2, q);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L25" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Note that f does not evaluate, and that f(x) is an expression.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L26" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">f; f(x);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L28" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle161"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle161">Using the unapply command you can convert an expression into a function:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle161"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L29" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle157">q := sin(x^2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L30" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle157">g := unapply(q,x);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L31" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle157">g(y);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L32" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">The command diff can be used to differentiate functions/expressions</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L551" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">dg := diff(g(x),x);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L33" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">dq := diff(q,x);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L34" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Unfortunately, diff does not return a function but an expression. We can cast it into a function with the command unapply: </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L35" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">dg := unapply(dg,x);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L36" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">...however, the command D returns a function directly.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L37" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">dg := D(g);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L556" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">dg(z);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L38" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">We prefer to use functions above expressions in the recipes that follow below.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L41" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Functions of more variables are defined very similar, as</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L42" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">r := (x, y) -&gt; sqrt(x^2 + y^2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L43" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">r(s,t);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L44" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Differentiating with respect to x gives</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L45" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">diff(r(x,y),x);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L46" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_pstyle162" layout="_pstyle162">The D command can also be used for taking partial derivatives and returning a function: </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L47" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">drdx := D[1](r);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L48" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">drdy := D[2](r);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L651" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Plotting functions and expressions can be done as follows:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L644" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">plot([g(x), 2*q], x=-2..3, labels=[&quot;x&quot;, &quot;y&quot;], legend=[&quot;f&quot;,&quot;2 q&quot;]);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L652" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">p:=%:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L643" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">Pl2 := display(p,labelfont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16],legendstyle = [font=[&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16]],titlefont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16], axesfont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, &quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16]):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L646" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(default):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L648" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">display(Pl2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L645" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(ps,plotoutput=&quot;cookbook_plot_f.eps&quot;,plotoptions=`portrait,noborder,width=500,height=400`);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L647" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">display(Pl2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L650" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(default):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L642" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L49" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle8" layout="_pstyle163">Lists, sets, sequences, Arrays, Matrices and Vectors</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">A mathematical as well as a programming  language, Maple has quite a number of native data types, which can be confusing when starting with Maple.  The sequence is one of the </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">most basic data types:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L50" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">a := 1,2,3,2,1; b := 1,2,3,4,5; a[3];</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"> </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L51" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">An important feature that we will use occasionally is that it is very easy to append elements to sequences.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">pp := NULL defines pp as an empty sequence </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L52" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">c := NULL; # start with an empty sequence</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L53" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">c := c, 1;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L54" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">c := c, 2;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L55" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">However, the capabilities of sequences are quite limited. For more features, there are the list [] and set {} types. Lists can have doubles and preserve order, whereas sets don't. The essential difference between set / lists and sequences is that sets/lists are regarded as one object, whereas sequences aren't.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L56" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">set_a := { a };</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L57" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">list_a := [ a ];</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L58" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">The seq command can generate new sequences. It is very powerful and we will need it regularly.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L59" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">seq(i^2, i=1..5);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L60" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Below we will demonstrate the use of seq to combine the sequences a and b into a sequence of list pairs, which can be used to plot the data. </Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Note the detail that plot requires a list (one object) and not a sequence.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L664" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">p := seq([a[i], b[i]], i=1..5);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L666" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154"></Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">plot([p]);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L675" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">P:=%:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L676" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">Pl2 := display(P,labelfont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16],legendstyle = [font=[&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16]],titlefont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16], axesfont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, &quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16]):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L674" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">#? plot</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L671" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(default):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L673" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">display(Pl2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L678" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(ps,plotoutput=&quot;cookbook_plot_list.eps&quot;,plotoptions=`portrait,noborder,width=500,height=400`);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L672" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">display(Pl2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L677" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(default):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L61" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L62" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">To convert a list into a sequence use op, for the number of elements in the list/set use nops.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L63" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">list_a; </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L64" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">op(list_a);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L65" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">nops(list_a);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L66" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Many a time you will want to store data while running through a loop, for example. If you know up front how many elements your data will contain, Arrays are the way to go. Arrays can be declared in various ways, as shown below.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L67" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">t := Array(1..10);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L68" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">t := Array(1..5, 1);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L69" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">t := Array([5,3,4,1,2]);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L70" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">t := Array(1..5, i -&gt; i);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L71" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">t := Array(1..5, i -&gt; i^2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L72" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">In the last two examples, an initialization function is used, which uses the index of an Array-element to calculate its value.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L73" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L74" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_pstyle164" layout="_pstyle164"><Font style="Text"> </Font><Font style="_cstyle46">Calculating sums &amp; products</Font></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle164" layout="_pstyle164"><Font style="Text">Note the following maple </Font><Font style="_cstyle47">oddity</Font><Font style="Text"> with regard to the 'sum' and 'prod' command:</Font></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L291" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle165">sum(t[i],i=1..5);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L292" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle165">prod(t[i],i=1..5);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L290" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L77" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_pstyle162" layout="_pstyle162"><Font style="Text">Instead use the commands </Font>'add' and 'mul'</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L78" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">add(t[i],i=1..5);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L79" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">mul(t[i],i=1..5);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L80" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Higher dimensional Arrays are easily created as follows.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L81" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">t := Array(1..5, 1..5);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L82" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">t := Array(1..5, 1..5, (i, j) -&gt; i^2 + j^2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L83" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Matrices and Vectors are basic objects in Maple, and are used as follows:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L711" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">A := Matrix([[1,2],[3,4]]);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L84" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">b := Vector([1,2]);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L85" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Alternatively, you can use a shorthand notation with &lt;, &gt; and | symbols. Pay attention that | indicates a column seperation!</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L713" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">Aa := &lt;&lt;1,2&gt;|&lt;3,4&gt;&gt;;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L86" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">ba := &lt;1,2&gt;;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L87" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Note that Aa is not equal to A!</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L88" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">A - Aa;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L90" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">The functionality of linear algebra is contained in the LinearAlgebra package, which can be included as follows:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L91" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">with(LinearAlgebra):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L92" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">The inverse of A can now simply be found by:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L93" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">Ainv := MatrixInverse(A);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L94" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Say we want to solve A y = b. The vector y can now be found by:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L95" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">y := Ainv . b;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L96" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Which is indeed the solution as verified below.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L97" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">b - A . y;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L98" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_pstyle164" layout="_pstyle164"><Font style="_cstyle46">Important: Always type Array, Matrix and Vector with a capital</Font><Font style="Text">. </Font></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">The types array, matrix and vector exist as well, but are obsolete and work slightly different.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L99" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle10" layout="_pstyle166">For-loops</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L100" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150">Frequently we will want to study the behavior of the equations over complete parameter spaces, which can be done with for-loops. These loops are relatively slow, so care needs to be taken when applying them. 
</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L101" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">f := x -&gt; sin(x):</Text-field>
</Input>
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">N := 25:</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">X := Array(1..N):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">Y := Array(1..N):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">for i from 1 to N do</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">  X[i] := (i-1)*(2*Pi)/(N-1):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">  Y[i] := f(X[i]):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">od:</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">X[1..10]; Y[1..10];</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L103" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">For computation speed it may be worthwhile to insert the 'evalf' command</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L515" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">N := 25:</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">X := Array(1..N):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">Y := Array(1..N):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">for i from 1 to N do</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">  X[i] := evalf((i-1)*(2*Pi)/(N-1)):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">  Y[i] := evalf(f(X[i])):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">od:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L104" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">X[1..5]; </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L105" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Create a list of x,y pairs and plot the discrete sine function. The syntax of the plot command for data points is explained below.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L106" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">pp := seq([X[i], Y[i]], i=1..N):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">plot([pp], style=point,labels=[&quot;x&quot;,&quot;y&quot;],symbolsize=15,symbol=circle);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L728" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">P:=%:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L729" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">Pl2 := display(P,labelfont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16],legendstyle = [font=[&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16]],titlefont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16], axesfont = [&quot;HELVETICA&quot;, &quot;HELVETICA&quot;, 16]):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L725" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(default):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L727" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">display(Pl2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L731" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(ps,plotoutput=&quot;cookbook_plot_pointplot.eps&quot;,plotoptions=`portrait,noborder,width=500,height=400`);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L726" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">display(Pl2);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L730" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">plotsetup(default):</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L724" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L107" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">Occasionally, it may be more convenient to use a list to store our data. This is done as follows:</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L108" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">N := 25:</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">pp := NULL:</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">for i from 1 to N do</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">  x := (i-1)*(2*Pi)/(N-1):</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">  pp := pp, [x, f(x)]:</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">od:</Text-field>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">pp;</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L109" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle10" layout="_pstyle166">Converting datatypes.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="_cstyle3" layout="_pstyle150"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">We will regularly need to convert data types, as different Maple commands require different data types.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155">We can check the datatype by the command whattype.</Text-field>
<Text-field style="Text" layout="_pstyle155"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L110" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">x := 1; l := [1,2,3,4]; s := 1,2,3,4; A := Array([1,2,3,4]); M := Matrix([[1,2],[3,4]]); V := Vector([1,2,3,4]);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L111" drawlabel="true">
<Input>
<Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="_pstyle154">whattype(x); whattype(l); whattype(s); whattype(A); whattype(M); whattype(V);</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
